# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: symbolic-computation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] In the theory of multivariate polynomials, **Buchberger's algorithm** is a method for transforming a given set of polynomials into a Gröbner basis, which is another set of polynomials that have the same common zeros and are more convenient for extracting information on these common zeros.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] It was introduced by Bruno Buchberger simultaneously with the definition of Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] The Euclidean algorithm for computing the polynomial greatest common divisor is a special case of Buchberger's algorithm restricted to polynomials of a single variable.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Gaussian elimination of a system of linear equations is another special case where the degree of all polynomials equals one.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] For other Gröbner basis algorithms, see Gröbner basis § Algorithms and implementations.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] For every *fi*, *fj* in *G*, denote by *gi* the leading term of *fi* with respect to the given monomial ordering, and by *aij* the least common multiple of *gi* and *gj*.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Choose two polynomials in *G* and let *S**ij* = ⁠*a**ij*/ *g**i*⁠ *f**i* − ⁠*a**ij*/ *g**j*⁠ *f**j* *(The leading terms here will cancel by construction)*.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Reduce *S**ij*, with the multivariate division algorithm relative to the set *G* until the result is not further reducible.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] If the result is non-zero, add it to *G*.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Repeat steps 2–4 until all possible pairs are considered, including those involving the new polynomials added in step 4.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] The polynomial *S**ij* is commonly referred to as the *S*-polynomial, where *S* refers to *subtraction* (Buchberger) or *syzygy* (others).
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] The pair of polynomials with which it is associated is commonly referred to as critical pair.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] There are many ways to improve this algorithm beyond what has been stated above.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] For example, all the new elements of *F* can be reduced relative to each other before adding them.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] If the leading terms of *fi* and *fj* share no variables in common, then *Sij* will *always* reduce to 0 (if using only fi and fj for reduction), so it needn't be calculated at all.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] The algorithm terminates because it is consistently increasing the size of the monomial ideal generated by the leading terms of our set *F*, and Dickson's lemma (or the Hilbert basis theorem) guarantees that any such ascending chain must eventually become constant.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] The computational complexity of Buchberger's algorithm is very difficult to estimate, because of the number of choices that may dramatically change the computation time.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] where *n* is the number of variables, and *d* the maximal total degree of the input polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] This allows, in theory, to use linear algebra over the vector space of the polynomials of degree bounded by this value, for getting an algorithm of complexity $d^{2^{n+o(1)}}$ .
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] and the above upper bound of complexity is optimal.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Nevertheless, such examples are extremely rare.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Since its discovery, many variants of Buchberger's have been introduced to improve its efficiency.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] Faugère's F4 and F5 algorithms are presently the most efficient algorithms for computing Gröbner bases, and allow to compute routinely Gröbner bases consisting of several hundreds of polynomials, having each several hundreds of terms and coefficients of several hundreds of digits.
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] At least one implementation of Buchberger’s algorithm has been proved correct within the proof assistant Rocq (formerly named Coq).
[src:symbolic-computation/buchberger-s-algorithm] In the SymPy library for Python, the (improved) Buchberger algorithm is implemented as `sympy.polys.polytools.groebner()`.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] A **computer algebra system** (**CAS**) or **symbolic algebra system** (**SAS**) is any mathematical software with the ability to manipulate mathematical expressions in a way similar to the traditional manual computations of mathematicians and scientists.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The development of the computer algebra systems in the second half of the 20th century is part of the discipline of "computer algebra" or "symbolic computation", which has spurred work in algorithms over mathematical objects such as polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Computer algebra systems may be divided into two classes: specialized and general-purpose.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The specialized ones are devoted to a specific part of mathematics, such as number theory, group theory, or teaching of elementary mathematics.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] General-purpose computer algebra systems aim to be useful to a user working in any scientific field that requires manipulation of mathematical expressions.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The library must not only provide for the needs of the users, but also the needs of the simplifier.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] For example, the computation of polynomial greatest common divisors is systematically used for the simplification of expressions involving fractions.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] This large amount of required computer capabilities explains the small number of general-purpose computer algebra systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Significant systems include Axiom, GAP, Maxima, Magma, Maple, Mathematica, SageMath, and SymPy.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] In the 1950s, while computers were mainly used for numerical computations, there were some research projects into using them for symbolic manipulation.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Computer algebra systems began to appear in the 1960s and evolved out of two quite different sources—the requirements of theoretical physicists and research into artificial intelligence.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] A prime example of the first development was the pioneering work conducted by the later Nobel Prize laureate in physics Martinus Veltman, who designed a program for symbolic mathematics, especially high-energy physics, called Schoonschip (Dutch for "clean ship") in 1963.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Using Lisp as the programming basis, Carl Engelman created MATHLAB in 1964 at MITRE within an artificial-intelligence research environment.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] MATHLAB was later made available to users on PDP-6 and PDP-10 systems running TOPS-10 or TENEX in universities.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Today it can still be used on SIMH emulations of the PDP-10.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] MATHLAB ("**math**ematical **lab**oratory") should not be confused with MATLAB ("**mat**rix **lab**oratory"), which is a system for numerical computation built 15 years later at the University of New Mexico.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] In 1987, Hewlett-Packard introduced the first hand-held calculator CAS with the HP-28 series.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Other early handheld calculators with symbolic algebra capabilities included the Texas Instruments TI-89 series and TI-92 calculator, and the Casio CFX-9970G.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The first popular computer algebra systems were muMATH, Reduce, Derive (based on muMATH), and Macsyma; a copyleft version of Macsyma is called Maxima.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Commercial systems include Mathematica and Maple, which are commonly used by research mathematicians, scientists, and engineers.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Freely available alternatives include SageMath (which can act as a front-end to several other free and nonfree CAS).
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Other significant systems include Axiom, GAP, Maxima and Magma.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The movement to web-based applications in the early 2000s saw the release of WolframAlpha, an online search engine and CAS which includes the capabilities of Mathematica.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] More recently, computer algebra systems have been implemented using artificial neural networks.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] In the above, the word *some* indicates that the operation cannot always be performed.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Some computer algebra systems focus on specialized disciplines; these are typically developed in academia and are free.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] They can be inefficient for numeric operations as compared to numeric systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Numeric domains supported typically include floating-point representation of real numbers, integers (of unbounded size), complex (floating-point representation), interval representation of reals, rational number (exact representation) and algebraic numbers.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] There have been many advocates for increasing the use of computer algebra systems in primary and secondary-school classrooms.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The primary reason for such advocacy is that computer algebra systems represent real-world math more than do paper-and-pencil or hand calculator based mathematics.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] This push for increasing computer usage in mathematics classrooms has been supported by some boards of education.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] It has even been mandated in the curriculum of some regions.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Computer algebra systems have been extensively used in higher education.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] Many universities offer either specific courses on developing their use, or they implicitly expect students to use them for their course work.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] The companies that develop computer algebra systems have pushed to increase their prevalence among university and college programs.
[src:symbolic-computation/computer-algebra-system] CAS-equipped calculators are not permitted on the ACT, the PLAN, the SAT, and in some classrooms though it may be permitted on College Board's calculator-permitted AP tests, including the AP Calculus, Chemistry, Physics, and Statistics exams.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In mathematics, and more specifically in computer algebra, computational algebraic geometry, and computational commutative algebra, a **Gröbner basis** is a particular kind of generating set of an ideal in a polynomial ring $K[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ over a field K .
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] A Gröbner basis allows many important properties of the ideal and the associated algebraic variety to be deduced easily, such as the dimension and the number of zeros when it is finite.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Gröbner basis computation is one of the main practical tools for solving systems of polynomial equations and computing the images of algebraic varieties under projections or rational maps.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Gröbner basis computation can be seen as a multivariate, non-linear generalization of both Euclid's algorithm for computing polynomial greatest common divisors, and Gaussian elimination for linear systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Gröbner bases were introduced by Bruno Buchberger in his 1965 Ph.D. thesis, which also included an algorithm to compute them (Buchberger's algorithm).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] He named them after his advisor Wolfgang Gröbner.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In 2007, Buchberger received the Association for Computing Machinery's Paris Kanellakis Theory and Practice Award for this work.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] However, the Russian mathematician Nikolai Günther had introduced a similar notion in 1913, published in various Russian mathematical journals.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] These papers were largely ignored by the mathematical community until their rediscovery in 1987 by Bodo Renschuch *et al.* An analogous concept for multivariate power series was developed independently by Heisuke Hironaka in 1964, who named them **standard bases**.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This term has been used by some authors to also denote Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The theory of Gröbner bases has been extended by many authors in various directions.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It has been generalized to other structures such as polynomials over principal ideal rings or polynomial rings, and also some classes of non-commutative rings and algebras, like Ore algebras.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Gröbner bases are primarily defined for ideals in a polynomial ring $R=K[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ over a field K.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Although the theory works for any field, most Gröbner basis computations are done either when K is the field of rationals or the integers modulo a prime number.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The vector $A=[a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}]$ is called the *exponent vector* of the monomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Monomials are uniquely defined by their exponent vectors, and, when a monomial ordering (see below) is fixed, a polynomial is uniquely represented by the ordered list of the ordered pairs formed by an exponent vector and the corresponding coefficient.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This representation of polynomials is especially efficient for Gröbner basis computation in computers, although it is less convenient for other computations such as polynomial factorization and polynomial greatest common divisor.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] All operations related to Gröbner bases require the choice of a total order on the monomials, with the following properties of compatibility with multiplication.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] A total order satisfying these condition is sometimes called an *admissible ordering*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] These conditions imply that the order is a well-order, that is, every strictly decreasing sequence of monomials is finite.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Gröbner basis theory was initially introduced for the lexicographical ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It was soon realised that the Gröbner basis for degrevlex is almost always much easier to compute, and that it is almost always easier to compute a lex Gröbner basis by first computing the degrevlex basis and then using a "change of ordering algorithm".
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] When elimination is needed, degrevlex is not convenient; both lex and lexdeg may be used but, again, many computations are relatively easy with lexdeg and almost impossible with lex.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Once a monomial ordering is fixed, the terms of a polynomial (a term is the product of a monomial with its nonzero coefficient) are naturally ordered by decreasing monomials (for this order).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This makes the representation of a polynomial as a sorted list of pairs coefficient–exponent vector a canonical representation of the polynomials (that is, two polynomials are equal if and only if they have the same representation).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The first (greatest) term of a polynomial p for this ordering and the corresponding monomial and coefficient are respectively called the *leading term*, *leading monomial* and *leading coefficient* and denoted, in this article, lt(*p*), lm(*p*) and lc(*p*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Most polynomial operations related to Gröbner bases involve the leading terms.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] So, the representation of polynomials as sorted lists make these operations particularly efficient (reading the first element of a list takes a constant time, independently of the length of the list).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] One says that M *divides* N, or that N is a *multiple* of M, if $a_{i}\leq b_{i}$ for every i; that is, if A is componentwise not greater than B.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In this case, the quotient ${\textstyle {\frac {N}{M}}}$ is defined as ${\textstyle {\frac {N}{M}}=x_{1}^{b_{1}-a_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{b_{n}-a_{n}}.}$ In other words, the exponent vector of ${\textstyle {\frac {N}{M}}}$ is the componentwise subtraction of the exponent vectors of N and M.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The *greatest common divisor* gcd(*M*, *N*) of M and N is the monomial ${\textstyle x_{1}^{\min(a_{1},b_{1})}\cdots x_{n}^{\min(a_{n},b_{n})}}$ whose exponent vector is the componentwise minimum of A and B.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The *least common multiple* lcm(*M*, *N*) is defined similarly with max instead of min.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The *reduction* of a polynomial by other polynomials with respect to a monomial ordering is central to Gröbner basis theory.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is a generalization of both row reduction occurring in Gaussian elimination and division steps of the Euclidean division of univariate polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] When completed as much as possible, it is sometimes called **multivariate division** although its result is not uniquely defined.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Let an admissible monomial ordering be fixed, to which refers every monomial comparison that will occur in this section.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] A polynomial f is *lead-reducible* by another polynomial g if the leading monomial lm(*f*) is a multiple of lm(*g*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The polynomial f is *reducible* by g if some monomial of f is a multiple of lm(*g*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Suppose that f is *reducible* by g, and let cm be a term of f such that the monomial m is a multiple of lm(*g*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This operation removes the monomial m from f without changing the terms with a monomial greater than m (for the monomial ordering).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In particular, a *one step lead-reduction* of f produces a polynomial all of whose monomials are smaller than lm(*f*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Given a finite set G of polynomials, one says that f is *reducible* or *lead-reducible* by G if it is reducible or lead-reducible, respectively, by at least one element g of G.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In this case, a one-step reduction (resp. one-step lead-reduction) of f by G is any one-step reduction (resp. one-step lead-reduction) of f by an element of G.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The (complete) reduction (resp. lead-reduction) of f by G consists of iterating one-step reductions (respect. one-step lead reductions) until getting a polynomial that is irreducible (resp. lead-irreducible) by G.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is sometimes called a *normal form* of f by G.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In general this form is not uniquely defined because there are, in general, several elements of G that can be used for reducing f; this non-uniqueness is the starting point of Gröbner basis theory.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] where h is irreducible by G and the $q_{g}$ are polynomials such that $\operatorname {lm} (q_{g}\,g)\leq \operatorname {lm} (f).$ In the case of univariate polynomials, if G consists of a single element g, then h is the remainder of the Euclidean division of f by g, and *q**g* is the quotient.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Moreover, the division algorithm is exactly the process of lead-reduction.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For this reason, some authors use the term *multivariate division* instead of reduction.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In the example that follows, there are exactly two complete lead-reductions that produce two very different results.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The fact that the results are irreducible (not only lead-irreducible) is specific to the example, although this is rather common with such small examples.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For the first reduction step, either the first or the second term of f may be reduced.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] However, the reduction of a term amounts to removing this term at the cost of adding new lower terms; if it is not the first reducible term that is reduced, it may occur that a further reduction adds a similar term, which must be reduced again.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is therefore always better to reduce first the largest (for the monomial order) reducible term; that is, in particular, to lead-reduce first until getting a lead-irreducible polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The leading term $-x^{2}y$ of $f_{1}$ is a multiple of the leading monomials of both $g_{1}$ and $g_{2},$ So, one has two choices for the second reduction step.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is for dealing with the problems set by this non-uniqueness that Buchberger introduced Gröbner bases and S-polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Intuitively, $0=f-f$ may be reduced to $f_{2}-f_{3}.$ This implies that $f_{2}-f_{3}$ belongs to the ideal generated by G.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] So, this ideal is not changed by adding $f_{3}-f_{2}$ to G, and this allows more reductions.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In particular, $f_{3}$ can be reduced to $f_{2}$ by $f_{3}-f_{2}$ and this restores the uniqueness of the reduced form.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] where lcm denotes the least common multiple of the leading monomials of f and g.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] where gcd denotes the greatest common divisor of the leading monomials of f and g.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] As the monomials that are reducible by both f and g are exactly the multiples of lcm, one can deal with all cases of non-uniqueness of the reduction by considering only the *S*-polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This is a fundamental fact for Gröbner basis theory and all algorithms for computing them.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This does not change anything to the theory since the two polynomials are associates.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Let $R=F[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ be a polynomial ring over a field F.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In this section, we suppose that an admissible monomial ordering has been fixed.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Let G be a finite set of polynomials in R that generates an ideal I.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] There are many characterizing properties, which can each be taken as an equivalent definition of Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For conciseness, in the following list, the notation "one-word/another word" means that one can take either "one-word" or "another word" for having two different characterizations of Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Counting the above definition, this provides 12 characterizations of Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The fact that so many characterizations are possible makes Gröbner bases very useful.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For every admissible monomial ordering and every finite set G of polynomials, there is a Gröbner basis that contains G and generates the same ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Moreover, such a Gröbner basis may be computed with Buchberger's algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The algorithm terminates always because of Dickson's lemma or because polynomial rings are Noetherian (Hilbert's basis theorem).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Condition 4 ensures that the result is a Gröbner basis, and the definitions of *S*-polynomials and reduction ensure that the generated ideal is not changed.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The above method is an algorithm for computing Gröbner bases; however, it is very inefficient.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Many improvements of the original Buchberger's algorithm, and several other algorithms have been proposed and implemented, which dramatically improve the efficiency.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] See § Algorithms and implementations, below.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] A Gröbner basis is **minimal** if all leading monomials of its elements are irreducible by the other elements of the basis.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Given a Gröbner basis of an ideal I, one gets a minimal Gröbner basis of I by removing the polynomials whose leading monomials are multiple of the leading monomial of another element of the Gröbner basis.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] However, if two polynomials of the basis have the same leading monomial, only one must be removed.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] So, every Gröbner basis contains a minimal Gröbner basis as a subset.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] All minimal Gröbner bases of a given ideal (for a fixed monomial ordering) have the same number of elements, and the same leading monomials, and the non-minimal Gröbner bases have more elements than the minimal ones.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] A Gröbner basis is **reduced** if every polynomial in it is irreducible by the other elements of the basis, and has 1 as leading coefficient.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] So, every reduced Gröbner basis is minimal, but a minimal Gröbner basis need not be reduced.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] All reduced Gröbner bases of an ideal (for a fixed monomial ordering) are equal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It follows that two ideals are equal if and only if they have the same reduced Gröbner basis.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Sometimes, reduced Gröbner bases are defined without the condition on the leading coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In this case, the uniqueness of reduced Gröbner bases is true only up to the multiplication of polynomials by a nonzero constant.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] When working with polynomials over the field $\mathbb {Q}$ of the rational numbers, it is useful to work only with polynomials with integer coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In this case, the condition on the leading coefficients in the definition of a reduced basis may be replaced by the condition that all elements of the basis are primitive polynomials with integer coefficients, with positive leading coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This restores the uniqueness of reduced bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For every monomial ordering, the empty set of polynomials is the unique Gröbner basis of the zero ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For every monomial ordering, a set of polynomials that contains a nonzero constant is a Gröbner basis of the unit ideal (the whole polynomial ring).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Conversely, every Gröbner basis of the unit ideal contains a nonzero constant.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The reduced Gröbner basis of the unit is formed by the single polynomial 1.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In the case of polynomials in a single variable, there is a unique admissible monomial ordering, the ordering by the degree.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The minimal Gröbner bases are the singletons consisting of a single polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The reduced Gröbner bases are the monic polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] As *f*, *k* and h belong to I, and none of them is reducible by the others, none of $\{f,k\},$ $\{f,h\},$ and $\{h,k\}$ is a Gröbner basis of I.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] can be reduced to zero by *f*, *k* and h.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The method that has been used here for finding h and k, and proving that {*f*, *k*, *h*} is a Gröbner basis is a direct application of Buchberger's algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] So, it can be applied mechanically to any similar example, although, in general, there are many polynomials and S-polynomials to consider, and the computation is generally too large for being done without a computer.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Unless explicitly stated, all the results that follow are true for any monomial ordering (see that article for the definitions of the different orders that are mentioned below).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is a common misconception that the lexicographical order is needed for some of these results.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Reduced Gröbner bases are *unique* for any given ideal and any monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Thus two ideals are equal if and only if they have the same (reduced) Gröbner basis (usually a Gröbner basis software always produces reduced Gröbner bases).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The reduction of a polynomial *f* by the Gröbner basis *G* of an ideal I yields 0 if and only if *f* is in I.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This allows to test the membership of an element in an ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Another method consists in verifying that the Gröbner basis of *G*∪{*f*} is equal to *G*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] To test if the ideal I generated by *f*1, ..., *f**k* is contained in the ideal J, it suffices to test that every *f**I* is in J.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] One may also test the equality of the reduced Gröbner bases of J and *J* ∪ {*f*1, ...,*f**k*}.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Any set of polynomials may be viewed as a system of polynomial equations by equating the polynomials to zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The set of the solutions of such a system depends only on the generated ideal, and, therefore does not change when the given generating set is replaced by the Gröbner basis, for any ordering, of the generated ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Such a solution, with coordinates in an algebraically closed field containing the coefficients of the polynomials, is called a *zero of the ideal*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In the usual case of rational coefficients, this algebraically closed field is chosen as the complex field.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] An ideal does not have any zero (the system of equations is inconsistent) if and only if 1 belongs to the ideal (this is Hilbert's Nullstellensatz), or, equivalently, if its Gröbner basis (for any monomial ordering) contains 1, or, also, if the corresponding reduced Gröbner basis is [1].
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Given the Gröbner basis *G* of an ideal *I*, it has only a finite number of zeros, if and only if, for each variable *x*, *G* contains a polynomial with a leading monomial that is a power of *x* (without any other variable appearing in the leading term).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] If this is the case, then the number of zeros, counted with multiplicity, is equal to the number of monomials that are not multiples of any leading monomial of *G*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This number is called the *degree* of the ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] When the number of zeros is finite, the Gröbner basis for a lexicographical monomial ordering provides, theoretically, a solution: the first coordinate of a solution is a root of the greatest common divisor of polynomials of the basis that depend only on the first variable.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] After substituting this root in the basis, the second coordinate of this solution is a root of the greatest common divisor of the resulting polynomials that depend only on the second variable, and so on.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This solving process is only theoretical, because it implies GCD computation and root-finding of polynomials with approximate coefficients, which are not practicable because of numeric instability.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Therefore, other methods have been developed to solve polynomial systems through Gröbner bases (see System of polynomial equations for more details).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The **dimension** of an ideal *I* in a polynomial ring *R* is the Krull dimension of the ring *R*/*I* and is equal to the dimension of the algebraic set of the zeros of *I*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is also equal to number of hyperplanes in general position which are needed to have an intersection with the algebraic set, which is a finite number of points.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The **degree** of the ideal and of its associated algebraic set is the number of points of this finite intersection, counted with multiplicity.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In particular, the degree of a hypersurface is equal to the degree of its definition polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The dimension depend only on the set of the leading monomials of the Gröbner basis of the ideal for any monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The same is true for the degree and degree-compatible monomial orderings; a monomial ordering is *degree compatible* if smaller for the degree implies smaller for the monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The dimension is the maximal size of a subset *S* of the variables such that there is no leading monomial depending only on the variables in *S*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Thus, if the ideal has dimension 0, then for each variable *x* there is a leading monomial in the Gröbner basis that is a power of x.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Both dimension and degree may be deduced from the Hilbert series of the ideal, which is the series ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{\infty }d_{i}t^{i}}$ , where $d_{i}$ is the number of monomials of degree *i* that are not multiple of any leading monomial in the Gröbner basis.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] where *d* is the dimension of the ideal and $P(t)$ is a polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The number $P(1)$ is the degree of the algebraic set defined by the ideal, in the case of a homogeneous ideal or a monomial ordering compatible with the degree; that is, to compare two monomials, one compares their total degrees first.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The dimension does not depend on the choice of a monomial ordering, although the Hilbert series and the polynomial $P(t)$ may change with changes of the monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] However, for homogeneous ideals or monomial orderings compatible with the degree, the Hilbert series and the polynomial $P(t)$ do not depend on the choice of monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Most computer algebra systems that provide functions to compute Gröbner bases provide also functions for computing the Hilbert series, and thus also the dimension and the degree.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The computation of Gröbner bases for an *elimination* monomial ordering allows computational elimination theory.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Consider a polynomial ring $K[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},y_{1},\ldots ,y_{m}]=K[X,Y],$ in which the variables are split into two subsets *X* and *Y*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Let us also choose an elimination monomial ordering "eliminating" *X*, that is a monomial ordering for which two monomials are compared by comparing first the *X*-parts, and, in case of equality only, considering the *Y*-parts.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This implies that a monomial containing an *X*-variable is greater than every monomial independent of *X*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] If *G* is a Gröbner basis of an ideal *I* for this monomial ordering, then $G\cap K[Y]$ is a Gröbner basis of $I\cap K[Y]$ (this ideal is often called the *elimination ideal*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Moreover, $G\cap K[Y]$ consists exactly of the polynomials of *G* whose leading terms belong to *K*[*Y*] (this makes the computation of $G\cap K[Y]$ very easy, as only the leading monomials need to be checked).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This *elimination property* has many applications, some described in the next sections.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The lexicographical ordering such that $x_{1}>\cdots >x_{n}$ is an elimination ordering for every partition $\{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{k}\},\{x_{k+1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}.$ Thus a Gröbner basis for this ordering carries much more information than usually necessary.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This may explain why Gröbner bases for the lexicographical ordering are usually the most difficult to compute.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] If I and J are two ideals generated respectively by {*f*1, ..., *f**m*} and {*g*1, ..., *g**k*}, then a single Gröbner basis computation produces a Gröbner basis of their intersection *I* ∩ *J*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For this, one introduces a new indeterminate *t*, and one uses an elimination ordering such that the first block contains only *t* and the other block contains all the other variables (this means that a monomial containing *t* is greater than every monomial that does not contain *t*).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In other words, *I* ∩ *J* is obtained by *eliminating* *t* in *K*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This may be proven by observing that the ideal *K* consists of the polynomials $(a-b)t+b$ such that $a\in I$ and $b\in J$ .
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] One may (and will) suppose that $f_{i}(t)$ and $g_{i}(t)$ are coprime (they have no non-constant common factors).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Implicitization consists in computing the implicit equations of such a curve.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In case of *n* = 2, that is for plane curves, this may be computed with the resultant.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In the other case, the resultant is a power of the result of the elimination.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] When modeling a problem by polynomial equations, it is often assumed that some quantities are non-zero, so as to avoid degenerate cases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For example, when dealing with triangles, many properties become false if the triangle degenerates to a line segment, i.e. the length of one side is equal to the sum of the lengths of the other sides.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In such situations, one cannot deduce relevant information from the polynomial system unless the degenerate solutions are ignored.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] More precisely, the system of equations defines an algebraic set which may have several irreducible components, and one must remove the components on which the degeneracy conditions are everywhere zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This is done by *saturating* the equations by the degeneracy conditions, which may be done via the elimination property of Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The localization of a ring consists in adjoining to it the formal inverses of some elements.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This section concerns only the case of a single element, or equivalently a finite number of elements (adjoining the inverses of several elements is equivalent to adjoining the inverse of their product).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The *localization* of a ring *R* by an element *f* is the ring $R_{f}=R[t]/(1-ft),$ where *t* is a new indeterminate representing the inverse of *f*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The *localization* of an ideal I of *R* is the ideal $I_{f}=R_{f}I$ of $R_{f}.$ When *R* is a polynomial ring, computing in $R_{f}$ is not efficient because of the need to manage the denominators.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Therefore, localization is usually replaced by the operation of *saturation*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] If J is the ideal generated by I and 1−*ft* in *R*[*t*], then $I:f^{\infty }=J\cap R.$ It follows that, if *R* is a polynomial ring, a Gröbner basis computation eliminating *t* produces a Gröbner basis of the saturation of an ideal by a polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Instead of using *F*, one may also start from a Gröbner basis of *F*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Which method is most efficient depends on the problem.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] However, if the saturation does not remove any component, that is if the ideal is equal to its saturated ideal, computing first the Gröbner basis of *F* is usually faster.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] On the other hand, if the saturation removes some components, the direct computation may be dramatically faster.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Hilbert's Nullstellensatz has two versions.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The first one asserts that a set of polynomials has no common zeros over an algebraic closure of the field of the coefficients, if and only if 1 belongs to the generated ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This is easily tested with a Gröbner basis computation, because 1 belongs to an ideal if and only if 1 belongs to the Gröbner basis of the ideal, for any monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The second version asserts that the set of common zeros (in an algebraic closure of the field of the coefficients) of an ideal is contained in the hypersurface of the zeros of a polynomial *f*, if and only if a power of *f* belongs to the ideal.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This may be tested by saturating the ideal by *f*; in fact, a power of *f* belongs to the ideal if and only if the saturation by *f* provides a Gröbner basis containing 1.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] One could guess that it suffices to eliminate the parameters to obtain the implicit equations of the variety, as it has been done in the case of curves.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Unfortunately this is not always the case.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] If the $p_{i}$ have a common zero (sometimes called *base point*), every irreducible component of the non-empty algebraic set defined by the $p_{i}$ is an irreducible component of the algebraic set defined by *I*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It follows that, in this case, the direct elimination of the $t_{i}$ provides an empty set of polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Eliminate the $t_{i}$ from G to get a Gröbner basis of the ideal (of the implicit equations) of the variety.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Buchberger's algorithm is the oldest algorithm for computing Gröbner bases.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It was devised by Bruno Buchberger together with the Gröbner basis theory.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] It is straightforward to implement, but it appeared soon that raw implementations can solve only trivial problems.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The integers occurring during a computation may be sufficiently large for making fast multiplication algorithms and multimodular arithmetic useful.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For this reason, most optimized implementations use the GMP library.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The choice of the S-polynomials to reduce and of the polynomials used for reducing them is devoted to heuristics.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] As in many computational problems, heuristics cannot detect most hidden simplifications, and if heuristic choices are avoided, one may get a dramatic improvement of the algorithm efficiency.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In most cases most S-polynomials that are computed are reduced to zero; that is, most computing time is spent to compute zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The monomial ordering that is most often needed for the applications (pure lexicographic) is not the ordering that leads to the easiest computation, generally the ordering *degrevlex*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] For solving 3. many improvements, variants and heuristics have been proposed before the introduction of F4 and F5 algorithms by Jean-Charles Faugère.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] As these algorithms are designed for integer coefficients or with coefficients in the integers modulo a prime number, Buchberger's algorithm remains useful for more general coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Roughly speaking, F4 algorithm solves 3. by replacing many S-polynomial reductions by the row reduction of a single large matrix for which advanced methods of linear algebra can be used.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This solves partially issue 4., as reductions to zero in Buchberger's algorithm correspond to relations between rows of the matrix to be reduced, and the zero rows of the reduced matrix correspond to a basis of the vector space of these relations.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] F5 algorithm improves F4 by introducing a criterion that allows reducing the size of the matrices to be reduced.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This criterion is almost optimal, since the matrices to be reduced have full rank in sufficiently regular cases (in particular, when the input polynomials form a regular sequence).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Tuning F5 for a general use is difficult, since its performances depend on an order on the input polynomials and a balance between the incrementation of the working polynomial degree and of the number of the input polynomials that are considered.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] To date (2022), there is no distributed implementation that is significantly more efficient than F4, but, over modular integers F5 has been used successfully for several cryptographic challenges; for example, for breaking HFE challenge.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Issue 5. has been solved by the discovery of basis conversion algorithms that start from the Gröbner basis for one monomial ordering for computing a Gröbner basis for another monomial ordering.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] FGLM algorithm is such a basis conversion algorithm that works only in the zero-dimensional case (where the polynomials have a finite number of complex common zeros) and has a polynomial complexity in the number of common zeros.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] A basis conversion algorithm that works is the general case is the *Gröbner walk algorithm*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In its original form, FGLM may be the critical step for solving systems of polynomial equations because FGML does not take into account the sparsity of involved matrices.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This has been fixed by the introduction of *sparse FGLM algorithms*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] When F4 is available, it is generally much more efficient than Buchberger's algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The implementation techniques and algorithmic variants are not always documented, although they may have a dramatic effect on efficiency.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Implementations of F4 and (sparse)-FGLM are included in the library *Msolve*.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Beside Gröbner algorithms, Msolve contains fast algorithms for real-root isolation, and combines all these functions in an algorithm for the real solutions of systems of polynomial equations that outperforms dramatically the other software for this problem (Maple and Magma).
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Msolve is available on GitHub, and is interfaced with Julia, Maple and SageMath; this means that Msolve can be used directly from within these software environments.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The complexity of the Gröbner basis computations is commonly evaluated in term of the number n of variables and the maximal degree d of the input polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In the worst case, the main parameter of the complexity is the maximal degree of the elements of the resulting reduced Gröbner basis.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The worst-case complexity of a Gröbner basis computation is doubly exponential in n.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] As every algorithm for computing a Gröbner basis must write its result, this provides a lower bound of the complexity.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The concept and algorithms of Gröbner bases have been generalized to submodules of free modules over a polynomial ring.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] In fact, if L is a free module over a ring R, then one may consider the direct sum $R\oplus L$ as a ring by defining the product of two elements of L to be 0.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] This allows identifying a submodule of L generated by $g_{1},\ldots ,g_{k}$ with the ideal of $R[e_{1},\ldots ,e_{l}]$ generated by $g_{1},\ldots ,g_{k}$ and the products $e_{i}e_{j}$ , $1\leq i\leq j\leq l$ .
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] If R is a polynomial ring, this reduces the theory and the algorithms of Gröbner bases of modules to the theory and the algorithms of Gröbner bases of ideals.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] The concept and algorithms of Gröbner bases have also been generalized to ideals over various rings, commutative or not, like polynomial rings over a principal ideal ring or Weyl algebras.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Gröbner bases have been applied in the theory of error-correcting codes for algebraic decoding.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] By using Gröbner basis computation on various forms of error-correcting equations, decoding methods were developed for correcting errors of cyclic codes, affine variety codes, algebraic-geometric codes and even general linear block codes.
[src:symbolic-computation/gröbner-basis] Applying Gröbner basis in algebraic decoding is still a research area of channel coding theory.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In algebra, the **greatest common divisor** (frequently abbreviated **GCD** or **gcd**) of two polynomials is a polynomial, of the highest possible degree, which is a factor of both the two original polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This concept is analogous to the greatest common divisor of two integers.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In the important case of univariate polynomials over a field, the polynomial GCD may be computed as for the integer GCD, with the Euclidean algorithm using long division.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The polynomial GCD is defined only up to the multiplication by an invertible constant.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The similarity between integer GCD and polynomial GCD allows extending to univariate polynomials all the properties that may be deduced from the Euclidean algorithm and Euclidean division.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Moreover, the polynomial GCD has specific properties that make it a fundamental notion in various areas of algebra.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Typically, the roots of the GCD of two polynomials are the common roots of the two polynomials, and this provides information on the roots without computing them.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The greatest common divisor may be defined and exists, more generally, for multivariate polynomials over a field, over the ring of integers, and over any unique factorization domain.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] There exist algorithms to compute them as soon as one has a GCD algorithm in the ring of coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] These algorithms proceed by a recursion on the number of variables to reduce the problem to a variant of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] They are a fundamental tool in computer algebra, because computer algebra systems use them systematically to simplify fractions: this was the motivation for much of the modern theory of polynomial GCD.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Let *p* and *q* be polynomials with coefficients in an integral domain *F*, typically a field or the integers.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] A **greatest common divisor** of *p* and *q* is a polynomial *d* that divides *p* and *q*, and such that every common divisor of *p* and *q* also divides *d*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Every pair of polynomials (not both zero) has a GCD if and only if *F* is a unique factorization domain.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If *F* is a field and *p* and *q* are not both zero, a polynomial *d* is a greatest common divisor if and only if it divides both *p* and *q*, and it has the greatest degree among the polynomials having this property.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If *p* = *q* = 0, the GCD is 0; however some authors consider that it is not defined in this case.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The greatest common divisor of *p* and *q* is usually denoted gcd(*p*, *q*).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The greatest common divisor is unique only up to multiplication by an invertible constant.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] For univariate polynomials over a field, one can instead choose the standard GCD to be the unique monic choice (having leading coefficient 1), but over more general coefficient rings there is no standard choice.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Therefore, equalities like *d* = gcd(*p*, *q*) or gcd(*p*, *q*) = gcd(*r*, *s*) should be understood to mean "*d* is a GCD of *p* and *q*" and "*p* and *q* have the same set of GCDs as *r* and *s*".
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In particular, gcd(*p*, *q*) = 1 means that the invertible constants are the only common divisors: in this case, by analogy with the ring of integers, one says that *p* and *q* are **coprime polynomials**.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] There are several ways to find the greatest common divisor of two polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *Euclidean algorithm*, which can be used to find the GCD of two polynomials in the same manner as for two numbers.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] To find the GCD of two polynomials using factoring, simply factor the two polynomials completely.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Then, take the product of all common factors.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] At this stage, we do not necessarily have a monic polynomial, so finally multiply this by a constant to make it a monic polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This will be the GCD of the two polynomials as it includes all common divisors and is monic.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Factoring polynomials can be difficult, especially if the polynomials have a large degree.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The Euclidean algorithm is a method that works for any pair of polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] It makes repeated use of Euclidean division.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] When using this algorithm on two numbers, the size of the numbers decreases at each stage.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] With polynomials, the degree of the polynomials decreases at each stage.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The last nonzero remainder, made monic if necessary, is the GCD of the two polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Since 12 *x* + 12 is the last nonzero remainder, it is a GCD of the original polynomials, and the monic GCD is *x* + 1.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In this example, it is not difficult to avoid introducing denominators by factoring out 12 before the second step.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This can always be done by using pseudo-remainder sequences, but, without care, this may introduce very large integers during the computation.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Therefore, for computer computation, other algorithms are used, that are described below.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This method works only if one can test the equality to zero of the coefficients that occur during the computation.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] So, in practice, the coefficients must be integers, rational numbers, elements of a finite field, or must belong to some finitely generated field extension of one of the preceding fields.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If the coefficients are floating-point numbers that represent real numbers that are known only approximately, then one must know the degree of the GCD for having a numerically stable result; in this case other techniques may be used, usually based on singular value decomposition.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The basic case of univariate polynomials over a field is especially important.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] It is the simplest example beyond the ring of integers, and this analogy is the source of the notion of Euclidean domain.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The theory and algorithms for the multivariate case and for coefficients in a unique factorization domain depend heavily on the basic case.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Polynomial GCD algorithms and derived algorithms allow one to get useful information on the roots of a polynomial, without computing them.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Euclidean division of polynomials, which is used in Euclid's algorithm for computing GCDs, is very similar to Euclidean division of integers.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Moreover, *q* and *r* are uniquely defined by these relations.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The difference from Euclidean division of the integers is that, for the integers, the degree is replaced by the absolute value, and that to have uniqueness one has to suppose that *r* is non-negative.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The rings for which such a theorem exists are called Euclidean domains.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Like for the integers, the Euclidean division of the polynomials may be computed by the long division algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This algorithm is usually presented for paper-and-pencil computation, but it works well on computers when formalized as follows (note that the names of the variables correspond exactly to the regions of the paper sheet in a pencil-and-paper computation of long division).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In the following computation "deg" stands for the degree of its argument (with the convention deg(0) < 0), and "lc" stands for the leading coefficient, the coefficient of the highest degree of the variable.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The proof of the validity of this algorithm relies on the fact that during the whole "while" loop, we have *a* = *bq* + *r* and deg(*r*) is a non-negative integer that decreases at each iteration.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus the proof of the validity of this algorithm also proves the validity of the Euclidean division.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] As for the integers, the Euclidean division allows us to define Euclid's algorithm for computing GCDs.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Starting from two polynomials *a* and *b*, Euclid's algorithm consists of recursively replacing the pair (*a*, *b*) by (*b*, rem(*a*, *b*)) (where "rem(*a*, *b*)" denotes the remainder of the Euclidean division, computed by the algorithm of the preceding section), until *b* = 0.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The sequence of the degrees of the *ri* is strictly decreasing.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus after, at most, deg(*b*) steps, one get a null remainder, say *rk*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] As (*a*, *b*) and (*b*, rem(*a*,*b*)) have the same divisors, the set of the common divisors is not changed by Euclid's algorithm and thus all pairs (*ri*, *r**i*+1) have the same set of common divisors.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The common divisors of a and b are thus the common divisors of *r**k*−1 and 0.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This not only proves that Euclid's algorithm computes GCDs but also proves that GCDs exist.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Bézout's identity is a GCD related theorem, initially proved for the integers, which is valid for every principal ideal domain.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In the case of the univariate polynomials over a field, it may be stated as follows.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The interest of this result in the case of the polynomials is that there is an efficient algorithm to compute the polynomials u and v.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This algorithm differs from Euclid's algorithm by a few more computations done at each iteration of the loop.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] It is therefore called **extended GCD algorithm**.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Another difference with Euclid's algorithm is that it also uses the quotient, denoted "quo", of the Euclidean division instead of only the remainder.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] An interesting feature of this algorithm is that, when the coefficients of Bezout's identity are needed, one gets for free the quotient of the input polynomials by their GCD.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] An important application of the extended GCD algorithm is that it allows one to compute division in algebraic field extensions.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Let L an algebraic extension of a field K, generated by an element whose minimal polynomial f has degree n.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The elements of L are usually represented by univariate polynomials over K of degree less than n.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The inverse of a non zero element a of L is the coefficient u in Bézout's identity *au* + *fv* = 1, which may be computed by extended GCD algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] (The GCD is 1 because the minimal polynomial f is irreducible.) The degree inequality in the specification of extended GCD algorithm shows that a further division by f is not needed to get deg(u) < deg(f).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In the case of univariate polynomials, there is a strong relationship between greatest common divisors and resultants.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] More precisely, the resultant of two polynomials *P*, *Q* is a polynomial function of the coefficients of *P* and *Q* which has the value zero if and only if the GCD of *P* and *Q* is not constant.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The theory of subresultantsis a generalization of this property that allows characterizing generically the GCD of two polynomials, and the resultant is the 0-th subresultant polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Every coefficient of the subresultant polynomials is defined as the determinant of a submatrix of the Sylvester matrix of *P* and *Q*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This implies that subresultants "specialize" well.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] More precisely, subresultants are defined for polynomials over any commutative ring *R*, and have the following property.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Let *φ* be a ring homomorphism of *R* into another commutative ring *S*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] It extends to another homomorphism, denoted also *φ* between the polynomials rings over *R* and *S*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Then, if *P* and *Q* are univariate polynomials with coefficients in *R* such that $\deg(P)=\deg(\varphi (P))$ and $\deg(Q)=\deg(\varphi (Q)),$ then the subresultant polynomials and the principal subresultant coefficients of *φ*(*P*) and *φ*(*Q*) are the image by *φ* of those of *P* and *Q*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The subresultants have two important properties which make them fundamental for the computation on computers of the GCD of two polynomials with integer coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Firstly, their definition through determinants allows bounding, through Hadamard inequality, the size of the coefficients of the GCD.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Secondly, this bound and the property of good specialization allow computing the GCD of two polynomials with integer coefficients through modular computation and Chinese remainder theorem (see below).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Let us denote by ${\mathcal {P}}_{i}$ the *K* vector space of dimension i of polynomials of degree less than i.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The resultant of *P* and *Q* is the determinant of the Sylvester matrix, which is the (square) matrix of $\varphi _{0}$ on the bases of the powers of *X*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *principal subresultant coefficient* *si* is the determinant of the *m* + *n* − 2*i* first rows of *Ti*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] First we add (*i* + 1) columns of zeros to the right of the (*m* + *n* − 2*i* − 1) × (*m* + *n* − 2*i* − 1) identity matrix.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] With this notation, the *i*-th *subresultant polynomial* is the determinant of the matrix product *ViTi*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Its coefficient of degree *j* is the determinant of the square submatrix of *Ti* consisting in its *m* + *n* − 2*i* − 1 first rows and the (*m* + *n* − *i* − *j*)-th row.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] It is not obvious that, as defined, the subresultants have the desired properties.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Nevertheless, the proof is rather simple if the properties of linear algebra and those of polynomials are put together.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] As defined, the columns of the matrix *Ti* are the vectors of the coefficients of some polynomials belonging to the image of $\varphi _{i}$ .
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If the degree of the GCD is greater than *i*, then Bézout's identity shows that every non zero polynomial in the image of $\varphi _{i}$ has a degree larger than *i*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If, on the other hand, the degree of the GCD is *i*, then Bézout's identity again allows proving that the multiples of the GCD that have a degree lower than *m* + *n* − *i* are in the image of $\varphi _{i}$ .
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The vector space of these multiples has the dimension *m* + *n* − 2*i* and has a base of polynomials of pairwise different degrees, not smaller than *i*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This implies that the submatrix of the *m* + *n* − 2*i* first rows of the column echelon form of *Ti* is the identity matrix and thus that *si* is not 0.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus *Si* is a polynomial in the image of $\varphi _{i}$ , which is a multiple of the GCD and has the same degree.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Most root-finding algorithms behave badly with polynomials that have multiple roots.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] It is therefore useful to detect and remove them before calling a root-finding algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] A GCD computation allows detection of the existence of multiple roots, since the multiple roots of a polynomial are the roots of the GCD of the polynomial and its derivative.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus the square-free factorization reduces root-finding of a polynomial with multiple roots to root-finding of several square-free polynomials of lower degree.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The square-free factorization is also the first step in most polynomial factorization algorithms.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *Sturm sequence* of a polynomial with real coefficients is the sequence of the remainders provided by a variant of Euclid's algorithm applied to the polynomial and its derivative.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Let *V*(*a*) be the number of changes of signs in the sequence, when evaluated at a point *a*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Sturm's theorem asserts that *V*(*a*) − *V*(*b*) is the number of real roots of the polynomial in the interval [*a*, *b*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus the Sturm sequence allows computing the number of real roots in a given interval.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] By subdividing the interval until every subinterval contains at most one root, this provides an algorithm that locates the real roots in intervals of arbitrary small length.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In this section, we consider polynomials over a unique factorization domain *R*, typically the ring of the integers, and over its field of fractions *F*, typically the field of the rational numbers, and we denote *R*[*X*] and *F*[*X*] the rings of polynomials in a set of variables over these rings.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *content* of a polynomial *p* ∈ *R*[*X*], denoted "cont(*p*)", is the GCD of its coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] A polynomial *q* ∈ *F*[*X*] may be written $q={\frac {p}{c}}$ where *p* ∈ *R*[*X*] and *c* ∈ *R*: it suffices to take for *c* a multiple of all denominators of the coefficients of *q* (for example their product) and *p* = *cq*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *content* of *q* is defined as: $\operatorname {cont} (q)={\frac {\operatorname {cont} (p)}{c}}.$ In both cases, the content is defined up to the multiplication by a unit of *R*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In both cases, it is a polynomial in *R*[*X*] that is *primitive*, which means that 1 is a GCD of its coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus every polynomial in *R*[*X*] or *F*[*X*] may be factorized as $p=\operatorname {cont} (p)\,\operatorname {primpart} (p),$ and this factorization is unique up to the multiplication of the content by a unit of *R* and of the primitive part by the inverse of this unit.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Gauss's lemma implies that the product of two primitive polynomials is primitive.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The relations of the preceding section imply a strong relation between the GCD's in *R*[*X*] and in *F*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] To avoid ambiguities, the notation "*gcd*" will be indexed, in the following, by the ring in which the GCD is computed.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus the computation of polynomial GCD's is essentially the same problem over *F*[*X*] and over *R*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] For univariate polynomials over the rational numbers, one may think that Euclid's algorithm is a convenient method for computing the GCD.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] However, it involves simplifying a large number of fractions of integers, and the resulting algorithm is not efficient.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] For this reason, methods have been designed to modify Euclid's algorithm for working only with polynomials over the integers.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] They consist of replacing the Euclidean division, which introduces fractions, by a so-called *pseudo-division*, and replacing the remainder sequence of the Euclid's algorithm by so-called *pseudo-remainder sequences* (see below).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In the previous section we have seen that the GCD of polynomials in *R*[*X*] may be deduced from GCDs in *R* and in *F*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] A closer look on the proof shows that this allows us to prove the existence of GCDs in *R*[*X*], if they exist in *R* and in *F*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In particular, if GCDs exist in *R*, and if *X* is reduced to one variable, this proves that GCDs exist in *R*[*X*] (Euclid's algorithm proves the existence of GCDs in *F*[*X*]).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] A polynomial in n variables may be considered as a univariate polynomial over the ring of polynomials in (*n* − 1) variables.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus a recursion on the number of variables shows that if GCDs exist and may be computed in *R*, then they exist and may be computed in every multivariate polynomial ring over *R*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In particular, if *R* is either the ring of the integers or a field, then GCDs exist in *R*[*x*1, ..., *xn*], and what precedes provides an algorithm to compute them.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In this section, we consider an integral domain *Z* (typically the ring **Z** of the integers) and its field of fractions *Q* (typically the field **Q** of the rational numbers).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Given two polynomials *A* and *B* in the univariate polynomial ring *Z*[*X*], the Euclidean division (over *Q*) of *A* by *B* provides a quotient and a remainder which may not belong to *Z*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *pseudo-division* has been introduced to allow a variant of Euclid's algorithm for which all remainders belong to *Z*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If $\deg(A)=a$ and $\deg(B)=b$ and *a* ≥ *b*, the **pseudo-remainder** of the pseudo-division of *A* by *B*, denoted by prem(*A*,*B*) is $\operatorname {prem} (A,B)=\operatorname {rem} (\operatorname {lc} (B)^{a-b+1}A,B),$ where lc(*B*) is the leading coefficient of *B* (the coefficient of *X**b*).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The pseudo-remainder of the pseudo-division of two polynomials in *Z*[*X*] belongs always to *Z*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Different choices of *α* give different pseudo-remainder sequences, which are described in the next subsections.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] As the common divisors of two polynomials are not changed if the polynomials are multiplied by invertible constants (in *Q*), the last nonzero term in a pseudo-remainder sequence is a GCD (in *Q*[*X*]) of the input polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Therefore, pseudo-remainder sequences allows computing GCD's in *Q*[*X*] without introducing fractions in *Q*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In some contexts, it is essential to control the sign of the leading coefficient of the pseudo-remainder.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This is typically the case when computing resultants and subresultants, or for using Sturm's theorem.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This control can be done either by replacing lc(*B*) by its absolute value in the definition of the pseudo-remainder, or by controlling the sign of α (if α divides all coefficients of a remainder, the same is true for −*α*).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The simplest (to define) remainder sequence consists in taking always *α* = 1.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In practice, it is not interesting, as the size of the coefficients grows exponentially with the degree of the input polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This is typical behavior of the trivial pseudo-remainder sequences.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *primitive pseudo-remainder sequence* consists in taking for α the content of the numerator.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Thus all the *r**i* are primitive polynomials.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The primitive pseudo-remainder sequence is the pseudo-remainder sequence, which generates the smallest coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] However it requires to compute a number of GCD's in *Z*, and therefore is not sufficiently efficient to be used in practice, especially when *Z* is itself a polynomial ring.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] A subresultant sequence can be also computed with pseudo-remainders.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The process consists in choosing α in such a way that every *r**i* is a subresultant polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Surprisingly, the computation of α is very easy (see below).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] On the other hand, the proof of correctness of the algorithm is difficult, because it should take into account all the possibilities for the difference of degrees of two consecutive remainders.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The coefficients in the subresultant sequence are rarely much larger than those of the primitive pseudo-remainder sequence.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] As GCD computations in *Z* are not needed, the subresultant sequence with pseudo-remainders gives the most efficient computation.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] They are obtained without any GCD computation, only exact divisions.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This makes this algorithm more efficient than that of primitive pseudo-remainder sequences.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The algorithm computing the subresultant sequence with pseudo-remainders is given below.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In this algorithm, the input (*a*, *b*) is a pair of polynomials in *Z*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The *r**i* are the successive pseudo remainders in *Z*[*X*], the variables *i* and *d**i* are non negative integers, and the Greek letters denote elements in *Z*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The functions `deg()` and `rem()` denote the degree of a polynomial and the remainder of the Euclidean division.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] In the algorithm, this remainder is always in *Z*[*X*].
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Finally the divisions denoted / are always exact and have their result either in *Z*[*X*] or in *Z*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Note: "lc" stands for the leading coefficient, the coefficient of the highest degree of the variable.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This algorithm computes not only the greatest common divisor (the last non zero *r**i*), but also all the subresultant polynomials: The remainder *r**i* is the (deg(*r**i*−1) − 1)-th subresultant polynomial.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] All the other subresultant polynomials are zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] One may use pseudo-remainders for constructing sequences having the same properties as Sturm sequences.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This requires to control the signs of the successive pseudo-remainders, in order to have the same signs as in the Sturm sequence.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This may be done by defining a modified pseudo-remainder as follows.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] For input polynomials with integer coefficients, this allows retrieval of Sturm sequences consisting of polynomials with integer coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The subresultant pseudo-remainder sequence may be modified similarly, in which case the signs of the remainders **coincide** with those computed over the rationals.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Note that the algorithm for computing the subresultant pseudo-remainder sequence given above will compute wrong subresultant polynomials if one uses $-\mathrm {prem2} (A,B)$ instead of $\operatorname {prem} (A,B)$ .
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If *f* and *g* are polynomials in *F*[*x*] for some finitely generated field *F*, the Euclidean Algorithm is the most natural way to compute their GCD.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] However, modern computer algebra systems only use it if *F* is finite because of a phenomenon called intermediate expression swell.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Although degrees keep decreasing during the Euclidean algorithm, if *F* is not finite then the bit size of the polynomials can increase (sometimes dramatically) during the computations because repeated arithmetic operations in *F* tends to lead to larger expressions.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] For example, the addition of two rational numbers whose denominators are bounded by *b* leads to a rational number whose denominator is bounded by *b*2, so in the worst case, the bit size could nearly double with just one operation.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] To expedite the computation, take a ring *D* for which *f* and *g* are in *D*[*x*], and take an ideal *I* such that *D*/*I* is a finite ring.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Then compute the GCD over this finite ring with the Euclidean Algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Using reconstruction techniques (Chinese remainder theorem, rational reconstruction, etc.) one can recover the GCD of *f* and *g* from its image modulo a number of ideals *I*.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] One can prove that this works provided that one discards modular images with non-minimal degrees, and avoids ideals *I* modulo which a leading coefficient vanishes.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] If we take $I=(2)$ then $D/I$ is a finite ring (not a field since I is not maximal in D ).
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] The Euclidean algorithm applied to the images of $f,g$ in $(D/I)[x]$ succeeds and returns 1.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] This implies that the GCD of $f,g$ in $F[x]$ must be 1 as well.
[src:symbolic-computation/polynomial-greatest-common-divisor] Note that this example could easily be handled by any method because the degrees were too small for expression swell to occur, but it illustrates that if two polynomials have GCD 1, then the modular algorithm is likely to terminate after a single ideal I .
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] In symbolic computation, the **Risch algorithm** is a method of indefinite integration used in some computer algebra systems to find antiderivatives.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] It is named after the American mathematician Robert Henry Risch, a specialist in computer algebra who developed it in 1968.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The algorithm transforms the problem of integration into a problem in algebra.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] It is based on the form of the function being integrated and on methods for integrating rational functions, radicals, logarithms, and exponential functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Risch called it a decision procedure, because it is a method for deciding whether a function has an elementary function as an indefinite integral, and if it does, for determining that indefinite integral.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] However, the algorithm does not always succeed in identifying whether or not the antiderivative of a given function in fact can be expressed in terms of elementary functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Specifically, the algorithm cannot solve the constant problem, which is undecidable when it needs to determine whether an arbitrary complex number expression is equal to zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The complete description of the Risch algorithm takes over 100 pages.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The **Risch–Norman algorithm** is a simpler, faster, but less powerful variant that was developed in 1976 by Arthur Norman.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Some significant progress has been made in computing the logarithmic part of a mixed transcendental-algebraic integral by Brian L.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The Risch algorithm is used to integrate elementary functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] These are functions obtained by composing exponentials, logarithms, radicals, trigonometric functions, and the four arithmetic operations (+ − × ÷).
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Laplace solved this problem for the case of rational functions, as he showed that the indefinite integral of a rational function is the sum of a rational function and a finite number of constant multiples of logarithms of rational functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The algorithm suggested by Laplace is usually described in calculus textbooks; as a computer program, it was finally implemented in the 1960s.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Liouville formulated the problem that is solved by the Risch algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Risch developed a method that allows one to consider only a finite set of functions of Liouville's form.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The intuition for the Risch algorithm comes from the behavior of the exponential and logarithm functions under differentiation.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] so if *eg* were in the result of an indefinite integration, it should be expected to be inside the integral.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] then if (ln *g*)*n* were in the result of an integration, then only a few powers of the logarithm should be expected.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Finding an elementary antiderivative is very sensitive to details.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] But if the constant term 71 is changed to 72, it is not possible to represent the antiderivative in terms of elementary functions, as FriCAS also shows.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Some computer algebra systems may here return an antiderivative in terms of *non-elementary* functions (i.e. elliptic integrals), which are outside the scope of the Risch algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] For example, Mathematica returns a result with the functions EllipticPi and EllipticF.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Integrals in the form $\int {\frac {x+A}{\sqrt {x^{4}+ax^{3}+bx^{2}+cx+d}}}\,dx$ were solved by Chebyshev (and in what cases it is elementary), but the strict proof for it was ultimately done by Zolotarev.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Some Davenport "theorems" are still being clarified.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] For example in 2020 a counterexample to such a "theorem" was found, where it turns out that an elementary antiderivative exists after all.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Transforming Risch's theoretical algorithm into an algorithm that can be effectively executed by a computer was a complex task which took a long time.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The case of the purely transcendental functions (which do not involve roots of polynomials) is relatively easy and was implemented early in most computer algebra systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The first implementation was done by Joel Moses in Macsyma soon after the publication of Risch's paper.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The case of purely algebraic functions was partially solved and implemented in Reduce by James H.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Davenport – for simplicity it could only deal with square roots and repeated square roots and not general radicals or other non-quadratic algebraic relations between variables.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The general case was solved and almost fully implemented in Scratchpad, a precursor of Axiom, by Manuel Bronstein, there is Axiom's fork FriCAS, with active Risch and other algorithm development on GitHub.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] However, the implementation did not include some of the branches for special cases completely.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] As of 2025, there is no full implementation of the Risch algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] The Risch algorithm applied to general elementary functions is not an algorithm but a semi-algorithm because it needs to check, as a part of its operation, if certain expressions are equivalent to zero (constant problem), in particular in the constant field.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] This issue also arises in the polynomial division algorithm; this algorithm will fail if it cannot correctly determine whether coefficients vanish identically.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Virtually every non-trivial algorithm relating to polynomials uses the polynomial division algorithm, the Risch algorithm included.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] If the constant field is computable, i.e., for elements not dependent on *x*, then the problem of zero-equivalence is decidable, so the Risch algorithm is a complete algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Examples of computable constant fields are ℚ and ℚ(*y*), i.e., rational numbers and rational functions in *y* with rational-number coefficients, respectively, where *y* is an indeterminate that does not depend on *x*.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] This is also an issue in the Gaussian elimination matrix algorithm (or any algorithm that can compute the nullspace of a matrix), which is also necessary for many parts of the Risch algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/risch-algorithm] Gaussian elimination will produce incorrect results if it cannot correctly determine whether a pivot is identically zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In mathematics and computer science, **computer algebra**, also called **symbolic computation** or **algebraic computation**, is a scientific area that refers to the study and development of algorithms and software for manipulating mathematical expressions and other mathematical objects.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Computer algebra is widely used to experiment in mathematics and to design the formulas that are used in numerical programs.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] It is also used for complete scientific computations, when purely numerical methods fail, as in public key cryptography, or for some non-linear problems.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Some authors distinguish *computer algebra* from *symbolic computation*, using the latter name to refer to kinds of symbolic computation other than the computation with mathematical formulas.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Some authors use *symbolic computation* for the computer-science aspect of the subject and *computer algebra* for the mathematical aspect.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In some languages, the name of the field is not a direct translation of its English name.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Typically, it is called *calcul formel* in French, which means "formal computation".
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This name reflects the ties this field has with formal methods.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] There is no learned society that is specific to computer algebra, but this function is assumed by the special interest group of the Association for Computing Machinery named SIGSAM (Special Interest Group on Symbolic and Algebraic Manipulation).
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] There are several annual conferences on computer algebra, the premier being ISSAC (International Symposium on Symbolic and Algebraic Computation), which is regularly sponsored by SIGSAM.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] There are several journals specializing in computer algebra, the top one being *Journal of Symbolic Computation* founded in 1985 by Bruno Buchberger.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] There are also several other journals that regularly publish articles in computer algebra.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] As numerical software is highly efficient for approximate numerical computation, it is common, in computer algebra, to emphasize *exact* computation with exactly represented data.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Such an exact representation implies that, even when the size of the output is small, the intermediate data generated during a computation may grow in an unpredictable way.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This behavior is called *expression swell*.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] To alleviate this problem, various methods are used in the representation of the data, as well as in the algorithms that manipulate them.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] The usual number systems used in numerical computation are floating point numbers and integers of a fixed, bounded size.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Neither of these is convenient for computer algebra, due to expression swell.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Therefore, the basic numbers used in computer algebra are the integers of the mathematicians, commonly represented by an unbounded signed sequence of digits in some base of numeration, usually the largest base allowed by the machine word.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] These integers allow one to define the rational numbers, which are irreducible fractions of two integers.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Programming an efficient implementation of the arithmetic operations is a hard task.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Therefore, most free computer algebra systems, and some commercial ones such as Mathematica and Maple, use the GMP library, which is thus a *de facto* standard.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Except for numbers and variables, every mathematical expression may be viewed as the symbol of an operator followed by a sequence of operands.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In computer-algebra software, the expressions are usually represented in this way.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This representation is very flexible, and many things that seem not to be mathematical expressions at first glance, may be represented and manipulated as such.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] For example, an equation may be considered as an expression with "=" as its leading operator, and a matrix may be represented as an expression with "matrix" as an operator and its rows as operands.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Even programs may be considered and represented as expressions with operator "procedure" and, at least, two operands, the list of parameters and the body, which is itself an expression with "body" as an operator and a sequence of instructions as operands.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Conversely, any mathematical expression may be viewed as a program.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] For example, the expression *a* + *b* may be viewed as a program for the addition, with *a* and *b* as parameters.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Executing this program consists of *evaluating* the expression for given values of *a* and *b*; if they are not given any values, then the result of the evaluation is simply its input.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This process of delayed evaluation is fundamental in computer algebra.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] As the size of the operands of an expression is unpredictable and may change during a working session, the sequence of the operands is usually represented as a sequence of either pointers (like in Macsyma) or entries in a hash table (like in Maple).
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] A simpler expression than this is generally desired, and simplification is needed when working with general expressions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This simplification is normally done through rewriting rules.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] There are several classes of rewriting rules to be considered.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] The simplest are rules that always reduce the size of the expression, like *E* − *E* → 0 or sin(0) → 0.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] They are systematically applied in computer algebra systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] A difficulty occurs with associative operations like addition and multiplication.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] The standard way to deal with associativity is to consider that addition and multiplication have an arbitrary number of operands; that is, that *a* + *b* + *c* is represented as "+"(*a*, *b*, *c*).
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In other words, in the internal representation of the expressions, there is no subtraction nor division nor unary minus, outside the representation of the numbers.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Another difficulty occurs with the commutativity of addition and multiplication.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] The problem is to quickly recognize the like terms in order to combine or cancel them.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Testing every pair of terms is costly with very long sums and products.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] To address this, Macsyma sorts the operands of sums and products into an order that places like terms in consecutive places, allowing easy detection.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In Maple, a hash function is designed for generating collisions when like terms are entered, allowing them to be combined as soon as they are introduced.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This allows subexpressions that appear several times in a computation to be immediately recognized and stored only once.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This saves memory and speeds up computation by avoiding repetition of the same operations on identical expressions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Some rewriting rules sometimes increase and sometimes decrease the size of the expressions to which they are applied.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This is the case for the distributive law or trigonometric identities.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] For the distributive law, the computer function that applies this rewriting rule is typically called "expand".
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] The reverse rewriting rule, called "factor", requires a non-trivial algorithm, which is thus a key function in computer algebra systems (see Polynomial factorization).
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Some fundamental mathematical questions arise when one wants to manipulate mathematical expressions in a computer.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] We consider mainly the case of the multivariate rational fractions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This is not a real restriction, because, as soon as the irrational functions appearing in an expression are simplified, they are usually considered as new indeterminates.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] There are two notions of equality for mathematical expressions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] *Syntactic equality* is the equality of their representation in a computer.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] It is known from Richardson's theorem that there may not exist an algorithm that decides whether two expressions representing numbers are semantically equal if exponentials and logarithms are allowed in the expressions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Accordingly, (semantic) equality may be tested only on some classes of expressions such as the polynomials and rational fractions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] To test the equality of two expressions, instead of designing specific algorithms, it is usual to put expressions in some *canonical form* or to put their difference in a *normal form*, and to test the syntactic equality of the result.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In computer algebra, "canonical form" and "normal form" are not synonymous.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] A *canonical form* is such that two expressions in canonical form are semantically equal if and only if they are syntactically equal, while a *normal form* is such that an expression in normal form is semantically zero only if it is syntactically zero.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In other words, zero has a unique representation as an expression in normal form.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Normal forms are usually preferred in computer algebra for several reasons.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Firstly, canonical forms may be more costly to compute than normal forms.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] For example, to put a polynomial in canonical form, one has to expand every product through the distributive law, while it is not necessary with a normal form (see below).
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Secondly, it may be the case, like for expressions involving radicals, that a canonical form, if it exists, depends on some arbitrary choices and that these choices may be different for two expressions that have been computed independently.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] This may make the use of a canonical form impractical.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Early computer algebra systems, such as the ENIAC at the University of Pennsylvania, relied on human computers or programmers to reprogram it between calculations, manipulate its many physical modules (or panels), and feed its IBM card reader.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Female mathematicians handled the majority of ENIAC programming human-guided computation: Jean Jennings, Marlyn Wescoff, Ruth Lichterman, Betty Snyder, Frances Bilas, and Kay McNulty led said efforts.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] In 1960, John McCarthy explored an extension of primitive recursive functions for computing symbolic expressions through the Lisp programming language while at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Early efforts at symbolic computation, in the 1960s and 1970s, faced challenges surrounding the inefficiency of long-known algorithms when ported to computer algebra systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Predecessors to Project MAC, such as ALTRAN, sought to overcome algorithmic limitations through advancements in hardware and interpreters, while later efforts turned towards software optimization.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] A large part of the work of researchers in the field consisted of revisiting classical algebra to increase its effectiveness while developing efficient algorithms for use in computer algebra.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] An example of this type of work is the computation of polynomial greatest common divisors, a task required to simplify fractions and an essential component of computer algebra.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Classical algorithms for this computation, such as Euclid's algorithm, proved inefficient over infinite fields; algorithms from linear algebra faced similar struggles.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-computation] Thus, researchers turned to discovering methods of reducing polynomials (such as those over a ring of integers or a unique factorization domain) to a variant efficiently computable via a Euclidean algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] The term *symbolic* is used to distinguish this problem from that of numerical integration, where the value of *F* is sought at a particular input or set of inputs, rather than a general formula for *F*.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Both problems were held to be of practical and theoretical importance long before the time of digital computers, but they are now generally considered the domain of computer science, as computers are most often used currently to tackle individual instances.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Finding the derivative of an expression is a straightforward process for which it is easy to construct an algorithm.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] The reverse question of finding the integral is much more difficult.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Many expressions that are relatively simple do not have integrals that can be expressed in closed form.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] See antiderivative and nonelementary integral for more details.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] In its original form, the Risch algorithm was not suitable for a direct implementation, and its complete implementation took a long time.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] It was first implemented in Reduce in the case of purely transcendental functions; the case of purely algebraic functions was solved and implemented in Reduce by James H.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Davenport; the general case was solved by Manuel Bronstein, who implemented almost all of it in Axiom, though to date there is no implementation of the Risch algorithm that can deal with all of the special cases and branches in it.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] However, the Risch algorithm applies only to *indefinite* integrals, while most of the integrals of interest to physicists, theoretical chemists, and engineers are *definite* integrals often related to Laplace transforms, Fourier transforms, and Mellin transforms.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Lacking a general algorithm, the developers of computer algebra systems have implemented heuristics based on pattern-matching and the exploitation of special functions, in particular the incomplete gamma function.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Although this approach is heuristic rather than algorithmic, it is nonetheless an effective method for solving many definite integrals encountered by practical engineering applications.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Earlier systems such as Macsyma had a few definite integrals related to special functions within a look-up table.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] However this particular method, involving differentiation of special functions with respect to its parameters, variable transformation, pattern matching and other manipulations, was pioneered by developers of the Maple system and then later emulated by Mathematica, Axiom, MuPAD and other systems.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] The main problem in the classical approach of symbolic integration is that, if a function is represented in closed form, then, in general, its antiderivative has not a similar representation.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] In other words, the class of functions that can be represented in closed form is not closed under antiderivation.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Holonomic functions are a large class of functions, which is closed under antiderivation and allows algorithmic implementation in computers of integration and many other operations of calculus.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] More precisely, a holonomic function is a solution of a homogeneous linear differential equation with polynomial coefficients.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Holonomic functions are closed under addition and multiplication, derivation, and antiderivation.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] They include algebraic functions, exponential function, logarithm, sine, cosine, inverse trigonometric functions, inverse hyperbolic functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] They include also most common special functions such as Airy function, error function, Bessel functions, and all hypergeometric functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] A fundamental property of holonomic functions is that the coefficients of their Taylor series at any point satisfy a linear recurrence relation with polynomial coefficients, and that this recurrence relation may be computed from the differential equation defining the function.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] Conversely given such a recurrence relation between the coefficients of a power series, this power series defines a holonomic function whose differential equation may be computed algorithmically.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] This recurrence relation allows a fast computation of the Taylor series, and thus of the value of the function at any point, with an arbitrary small certified error.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] This makes algorithmic most operations of calculus, when restricted to holonomic functions, represented by their differential equation and initial conditions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] This includes the computation of antiderivatives and definite integrals (this amounts to evaluating the antiderivative at the endpoints of the interval of integration).
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] This includes also the computation of the asymptotic behavior of the function at infinity, and thus the definite integrals on unbounded intervals.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] All these operations are implemented in the *algolib* library for Maple.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] See also the Dynamic Dictionary of Mathematical Functions.
[src:symbolic-computation/symbolic-integration] is a numerical result for the same definite integral.
